# 1. 心躍る舞台

Swordsman: “This swordsmanship...! You are no mere ogre, are you?!”
Ogre: “Hah! I have long since forgotten about my past!”
Emu: (Whoaaa...! Their swords are going all cling-clang-clash!)
Emu: (Their blades look like they're dancing, but they sound so solid whenever they meet.)
Tsukasa: (This is quite the spectacle...)
Tsukasa: (After learning more about sword fighting with Mikazukigumi, I have a much greater appreciation for just how difficult it is to move with such speed and precision.)
Rui: (The director must've put quite a lot of effort into making this scene feel so compelling.)
Rui: (You can tell that the costumes are meant to flutter a certain way.)
Nene: (They're also amazing singers. The all-female Suzurangumi troupe really wows you with their beauty and charm, while this one seems to be more about power and action...)
Nene: (There's more to it than just the fact that they're all boys. I mean, they're all performing at such a high level...)
Emu: (This is so cool...)
Emu: (I didn't know Kikyogumi was so amazing...!!)
Emu: Wooowww...
Tsukasa: That was an excellent performance...
Nene: Yeah. The scene at the end where the swordsman and the ogre part ways under the cherry blossoms... It was sad, but I like how they left room for them meeting again someday.
Rui: Yes, I noticed a few people in the audience tearing up.
Rui: In the beginning, they fought like only one of them would be left standing... I feel that the final scene was so moving because they presented us with such an epic battle.
Emu: Yeah! Everyone in the audience really got to understand the swordsman and ogre's feelings!
Emu: (But...)
Emu: (For some reason, there were a lot of empty seats...)
Emu: (Even though they put on such an amazing show.)
Tsukasa: Ah, we've been talking for quite a while now. We mustn't overstay our welcome...
Tsukasa: That being said, I'd love to discuss further. Why don't we all find a place where we can resume this conversation?
Emu: Yeah!
Rui: Then, why don't we try the diner by the station?
Nene: Sounds good. I could use a bite.
Tsukasa: Alright, then... Let's go!
Tsukasa: Phew... We really chatted up a storm.
Emu: Yeah! Talking about all our favorite scenes was super duper fun!
Nene: I also had fun. It's been a while since we got to talk like this...
Tsukasa: Yes, it has! After all, Rui and I are training with the boys, you're with the girls, Nene, and you've been learning all about management, Emu.
Nene: Speaking of which, what are you guys working on right now?
Rui: Tap dancing, until just recently. We'll be having lessons on traditional Japanese dance soon.
Emu: Oh, that's so cool!
Emu: You guys get to learn about so many different things!
Rui: Yes, but...
Emu: But?
Rui: How to put it... Things have felt a bit hectic lately.
Rui: For some reason, our teachers are constantly getting swapped in and out.
Emu: Really...?
Nene: Nothing like that's been happening on my end. What do you think is going on...?
Tsukasa: We have no idea... But I for one have been enjoying the chance to learn from so many different instructors.
Tsukasa: Each one focuses on the aspects they see as most important. In other words, we get to tackle a subject from many different angles.
Nene: Yeah, that is kinda nice...
Emu: Just like taiyaki shops. They're all really good, but also taste a little different!
Rui: Hehe. That seems like an apt comparison.
Nene: What about you, Emu? It seems like you're always doing something different. I remember you learning about being a producer one day and how to write proposals the next.
Emu: So, lately, I've been learning a lot about budgeting for day-to-day operations.
Emu: All the stuff about employee wages and maintenance costs are things I've heard about when it comes to Phoenix Wonderland.
Emu: But Morinomiya puts a lot of resources into their props and costumes because they want their audiences to “experience the extraordinary”.
Tsukasa: I see... In other words, resources are allocated differently depending on what a company wishes to achieve.
Emu: Yeah. It's been a lot to process, but I've also been having a lot of fun!
Rui: It sounds like you've been gaining quite a lot from this experience.
Emu: Hehe. Lots and lots of people at both Morinomiya and Phoenix Wonderland are working really hard to put smiles on everyone's faces.
Emu: Some problems are really, really hard to solve, and you sorta just have to take a leap of faith...
Emu: But I wanna become somebody who can help solve those kinds of problems.
Emu: Which is why I'm really enjoying what I'm doing right now!
Nene: I see...
Emu: Hehe. Oh, also!
Emu: The other day, when I was learning about administrative practices... Oh, wait!
Nene: ...? What's wrong?
Emu: So... That just reminded me of something...
Emu: I saw this really strange girl the other day!!
Tsukasa: A strange girl? What do you mean...?
Emu: So, there's this really fancy room where the executives hold their most important meetings...
Emu: And this girl around our age came walking out of it!
Tsukasa: She was in their meeting room?
Nene: Was she there as an official participant...?
Tsukasa: It's hard to believe that someone our age would be engaging with any executives.
Rui: Emu is a bit of an exception, and I feel that we would've heard about such a girl through word of mouth by now.
Rui: Maybe some of the other Morinomiya students could give us a clue...
Nene: This might actually be the perfect time...
Emu: Huh?
Nene: Umm... There's someone that I want you guys to meet.
Nene: She's a classmate and showed a lot of interest in our troupe...
Nene: She might know something, so wanna try asking her?
